{{root|en|ine-pro|*ret-}}
The {{glossary|adjective}} is derived from {{inh|en|enm|rash}}, {{m|enm|rasch|t=hasty, headstrong, rash}}{{nb...|rashe, rassh, rasshe|otherforms=1}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=rash(e|pos=adj|id=MED35947}}</ref> probably from {{inh|en|ang|*ræsc|t=rash}} (found in derivatives such as {{m|ang|ræscan|t=to move rapidly; to flicker; to flash; to glitter; to quiver}}, {{m|ang|ræscettan|t=to crackle; to sparkle}}, etc.), from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*raskaz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*raskuz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*raþskaz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*raþskuz|t=rash; rapid}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*ret-|t=to run, roll}}. The Middle English word was probably influenced by the cognates listed below.<ref name="OED">{{R:OED Online|pos=adj.'' and ''adv|id=158316|date=March 2022|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|alt=rash{{sup|1}}|pos=adj}}</ref>

The {{glossary|adverb}} is derived from {{inh|en|enm|rashe|t=quickly, rapidly}}, from {{m|enm|rash}}, {{m|enm|rasch|pos=adjective}} (see above).<ref name="OED"/><ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=rashe|pos=adv|id=MED35948}}</ref>

